# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: polygon-triangulation
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:polygon-triangulation/fan-triangulation] In computational geometry, a **fan triangulation** is a simple way to triangulate a polygon by choosing a vertex and drawing edges to all of the other vertices of the polygon.
[src:polygon-triangulation/fan-triangulation] Not every polygon can be triangulated this way, so this method is usually only used for convex polygons.
[src:polygon-triangulation/monotone-polygon] In geometry, a polygon P in the plane is called **monotone** with respect to a straight line L, if every line orthogonal to L intersects the boundary of P at most twice.
[src:polygon-triangulation/monotone-polygon] Similarly, a polygonal chain C is called **monotone** with respect to a straight line L, if every line orthogonal to L intersects C at most once.
[src:polygon-triangulation/monotone-polygon] For many practical purposes this definition may be extended to allow cases when some edges of P are orthogonal to L, and a simple polygon may be called monotone if a line segment that connects two points in P and is orthogonal to L lies completely in P.
[src:polygon-triangulation/monotone-polygon] Following the terminology for monotone functions, the former definition describes **polygons strictly monotone** with respect to L.
[src:polygon-triangulation/monotone-polygon] Assume that *L* coincides with the *x*-axis.
[src:polygon-triangulation/monotone-polygon] Then the leftmost and rightmost vertices of a monotone polygon decompose its boundary into two monotone polygonal chains such that when the vertices of any chain are being traversed in their natural order, their X-coordinates are monotonically increasing or decreasing.
[src:polygon-triangulation/monotone-polygon] In fact, this property may be taken for the definition of monotone polygon and it gives the polygon its name.
[src:polygon-triangulation/monotone-polygon] A convex polygon is monotone with respect to any straight line and a polygon which is monotone with respect to every straight line is convex.
[src:polygon-triangulation/monotone-polygon] A linear time algorithm is known to report all directions in which a given simple polygon is monotone.
[src:polygon-triangulation/monotone-polygon] Point in polygon queries with respect to a monotone polygon may be answered in logarithmic time after linear time preprocessing (to find the leftmost and rightmost vertices).
[src:polygon-triangulation/monotone-polygon] A monotone polygon may be easily triangulated in linear time.
[src:polygon-triangulation/monotone-polygon] For a given set of points in the plane, a bitonic tour is a monotone polygon that connects the points.
[src:polygon-triangulation/monotone-polygon] The minimum perimeter bitonic tour for a given point set with respect to a fixed direction may be found in polynomial time using dynamic programming.
[src:polygon-triangulation/monotone-polygon] It is easily shown that such a minimal bitonic tour is a simple polygon: a pair of crossing edges may be replaced with a shorter non-crossing pair while preserving the bitonicity of the new tour.
[src:polygon-triangulation/monotone-polygon] A simple polygon may be easily cut into monotone polygons in *O*(*n* log *n*) time.
[src:polygon-triangulation/monotone-polygon] However, since a triangle is a monotone polygon, polygon triangulation is in fact cutting a polygon into monotone ones, and it may be performed for simple polygons in *O*(*n*) time with a complex algorithm.
[src:polygon-triangulation/monotone-polygon] A simpler randomized algorithm with linear expected time is also known.
[src:polygon-triangulation/monotone-polygon] Cutting a simple polygon into the minimal number of uniformly monotone polygons (i.e., monotone with respect to the same line) can be performed in polynomial time.
[src:polygon-triangulation/monotone-polygon] In the context of motion planning, two nonintersecting monotone polygons are separable by a single translation (i.e., there exists a translation of one polygon such that the two become separated by a straight line into different halfplanes) and this separation may be found in linear time.
[src:polygon-triangulation/monotone-polygon] A polygon is called **sweepable**, if a straight line may be continuously moved over the whole polygon in such a way that at any moment its intersection with the polygonal area is a convex set.
[src:polygon-triangulation/monotone-polygon] A monotone polygon is sweepable by a line which does not change its orientation during the sweep.
[src:polygon-triangulation/monotone-polygon] A polygon is **strictly sweepable** if no portion of its area is swept more than once.
[src:polygon-triangulation/monotone-polygon] Both types of sweepability are recognized in quadratic time.
[src:polygon-triangulation/monotone-polygon] There is no single straightforward generalization of polygon monotonicity to higher dimensions.
[src:polygon-triangulation/monotone-polygon] In one approach the preserved monotonicity trait is the line *L*.
[src:polygon-triangulation/monotone-polygon] A three-dimensional polyhedron is called **weakly monotonic** in direction *L* if all cross-sections orthogonal to *L* are simple polygons.
[src:polygon-triangulation/monotone-polygon] If the cross-sections are convex, then the polyhedron is called **weakly monotonic in convex sense**.
[src:polygon-triangulation/monotone-polygon] Both types may be recognized in polynomial time.
[src:polygon-triangulation/monotone-polygon] In another approach the preserved one-dimensional trait is the orthogonal direction.
[src:polygon-triangulation/monotone-polygon] This gives rise for the notion of polyhedral terrain in three dimensions: a polyhedral surface with the property that each vertical (i.e., parallel to Z axis) line intersects the surface at most by one point or segment.
[src:polygon-triangulation/point-in-polygon] In computational geometry, the **point-in-polygon** (**PIP**) problem asks whether a given point in the plane lies inside, outside, or on the boundary of a polygon.
[src:polygon-triangulation/point-in-polygon] It is a special case of point location problems and finds applications in areas that deal with processing geometrical data, such as computer graphics, computer vision, geographic information systems (GIS), motion planning, and computer-aided design (CAD).
[src:polygon-triangulation/point-in-polygon] An early description of the problem in computer graphics shows two common approaches (ray casting and angle summation) in use as early as 1974.
[src:polygon-triangulation/point-in-polygon] An attempt of computer graphics veterans to trace the history of the problem and some tricks for its solution can be found in an issue of the *Ray Tracing News*.
[src:polygon-triangulation/point-in-polygon] One simple way of finding whether the point is inside or outside a simple polygon is to test how many times a ray, starting from the point and going in any fixed direction, intersects the edges of the polygon.
[src:polygon-triangulation/point-in-polygon] If the point is on the outside of the polygon the ray will intersect its edge an even number of times.
[src:polygon-triangulation/point-in-polygon] If the point is on the inside of the polygon then it will intersect the edge an odd number of times.
[src:polygon-triangulation/point-in-polygon] The status of a point on the edge of the polygon depends on the details of the ray intersection algorithm.
[src:polygon-triangulation/point-in-polygon] This algorithm is sometimes also known as the **crossing number algorithm** or the even–odd rule **algorithm**, and was known as early as 1962.
[src:polygon-triangulation/point-in-polygon] The algorithm is based on a simple observation that if a point moves along a ray from infinity to the probe point and if it crosses the boundary of a polygon, possibly several times, then it alternately goes from the outside to inside, then from the inside to the outside, etc.
[src:polygon-triangulation/point-in-polygon] As a result, after every two "border crossings" the moving point goes outside.
[src:polygon-triangulation/point-in-polygon] This observation may be mathematically proved using the Jordan curve theorem.
[src:polygon-triangulation/point-in-polygon] If implemented on a computer with finite-precision arithmetic, the results may be incorrect if the point lies very close to that boundary, because of rounding errors.
[src:polygon-triangulation/point-in-polygon] For some applications, like video games or other entertainment products, this is not a large concern since they often favor speed over precision.
[src:polygon-triangulation/point-in-polygon] Most implementations of the ray casting algorithm consecutively check intersections of a ray with all sides of the polygon in turn.
[src:polygon-triangulation/point-in-polygon] In this case the following problem must be addressed.
[src:polygon-triangulation/point-in-polygon] If the ray passes exactly through a vertex of a polygon, then it will intersect 2 segments at their endpoints.
[src:polygon-triangulation/point-in-polygon] While it is OK for the case of the topmost vertex in the example or the vertex between crossing 4 and 5, the case of the rightmost vertex (in the example) requires that we count one intersection for the algorithm to work correctly.
[src:polygon-triangulation/point-in-polygon] A similar problem arises with horizontal segments that happen to fall on the ray.
[src:polygon-triangulation/point-in-polygon] The issue is solved as follows: If the intersection point is a vertex of a tested polygon side, then the intersection counts only if the other vertex of the side lies below the ray.
[src:polygon-triangulation/point-in-polygon] This is effectively equivalent to considering vertices *on* the ray as lying slightly *above* the ray.
[src:polygon-triangulation/point-in-polygon] Once again, the case of the ray passing through a vertex may pose numerical problems in finite-precision arithmetic: for two sides adjacent to the same vertex the straightforward computation of the intersection with a ray may not give the vertex in both cases.
[src:polygon-triangulation/point-in-polygon] If the polygon is specified by its vertices, then this problem is eliminated by checking the y-coordinates of the ray and the ends of the tested polygon side before actual computation of the intersection.
[src:polygon-triangulation/point-in-polygon] In other cases, when polygon sides are computed from other types of data, other tricks must be applied for the numerical robustness of the algorithm.
[src:polygon-triangulation/point-in-polygon] Another technique used to check if a point is inside a polygon is to compute the given point's winding number with respect to the polygon.
[src:polygon-triangulation/point-in-polygon] If the winding number is non-zero, the point lies inside the polygon.
[src:polygon-triangulation/point-in-polygon] This algorithm is sometimes also known as the *nonzero-rule algorithm*.
[src:polygon-triangulation/point-in-polygon] One way to compute the winding number is to sum up the angles subtended by each side of the polygon.
[src:polygon-triangulation/point-in-polygon] However, this involves costly inverse trigonometric functions, which generally makes this algorithm performance-inefficient (slower) compared to the ray casting algorithm.
[src:polygon-triangulation/point-in-polygon] Luckily, these inverse trigonometric functions do not need to be computed.
[src:polygon-triangulation/point-in-polygon] Since the result, the sum of all angles, can add up to 0 or $2\pi$ (or multiples of $2\pi$ ) only, it is sufficient to track through which quadrants the polygon winds, as it turns around the test point, which makes the winding number algorithm comparable in speed to counting the boundary crossings.
[src:polygon-triangulation/point-in-polygon] An improved algorithm to calculate the winding number was developed by Dan Sunday in 2001.
[src:polygon-triangulation/point-in-polygon] It does not use angles in calculations, nor any trigonometry, and functions exactly the same as the ray casting algorithms described above.
[src:polygon-triangulation/point-in-polygon] Sunday's algorithm works by considering an infinite horizontal ray cast from the point being checked.
[src:polygon-triangulation/point-in-polygon] Whenever that ray crosses an edge of the polygon, Juan Pineda's edge crossing algorithm (1988) is used to determine how the crossing will affect the winding number.
[src:polygon-triangulation/point-in-polygon] As Sunday describes it, if the edge crosses the ray going "upwards", the winding number is incremented; if it crosses the ray "downwards", the number is decremented.
[src:polygon-triangulation/point-in-polygon] Sunday's algorithm gives the correct answer for nonsimple polygons, whereas the boundary crossing algorithm fails in this case.
[src:polygon-triangulation/point-in-polygon] Similar methods are used in SVG for defining a way of filling with color various shapes (such as path, polyline, polygon, text etc.).
[src:polygon-triangulation/point-in-polygon] The algorithm of filling is influenced by 'fill-rule' attribute.
[src:polygon-triangulation/point-in-polygon] The value may be either `nonzero` or `evenodd`.
[src:polygon-triangulation/point-in-polygon] For example, in a pentagram, there is a central "hole" (visible background) with `evenodd`, and none with `nonzero` attribute.
[src:polygon-triangulation/point-in-polygon] For simple polygons, the algorithms will give the same result.
[src:polygon-triangulation/point-in-polygon] However, for complex polygons, the algorithms may give different results for points in the regions where the polygon intersects itself, where the polygon does not have a clearly defined inside and outside.
[src:polygon-triangulation/point-in-polygon] One solution using the even-odd rule is to transform (complex) polygons into simpler ones that are even-odd-equivalent before the intersection check.
[src:polygon-triangulation/point-in-polygon] This, however, is computationally expensive.
[src:polygon-triangulation/point-in-polygon] It is less expensive to use the fast non-zero winding number algorithm, which gives the correct result even when the polygon overlaps itself.
[src:polygon-triangulation/point-in-polygon] The point in polygon problem may be considered in the general repeated geometric query setting: given a single polygon and a sequence of query points, quickly find the answers for each query point.
[src:polygon-triangulation/point-in-polygon] Clearly, any of the general approaches for planar point location may be used.
[src:polygon-triangulation/point-in-polygon] Simpler solutions are available for some special polygons.
[src:polygon-triangulation/point-in-polygon] Simpler algorithms are possible for monotone polygons, star-shaped polygons, convex polygons and triangles.
[src:polygon-triangulation/point-in-polygon] The triangle case can be solved easily by use of a barycentric coordinate system, parametric equation or dot product.
[src:polygon-triangulation/point-in-polygon] The dot product method extends naturally to any convex polygon.
[src:polygon-triangulation/polygon-triangulation] In computational geometry, **polygon triangulation** is the partition of a polygonal area (simple polygon) P into a set of triangles, i.e., finding a set of triangles with pairwise non-intersecting interiors whose union is P.
[src:polygon-triangulation/polygon-triangulation] Triangulations may be viewed as special cases of planar straight-line graphs.
[src:polygon-triangulation/polygon-triangulation] When there are no holes or added points, triangulations form maximal outerplanar graphs.
[src:polygon-triangulation/polygon-triangulation] Over time, a number of algorithms have been proposed to triangulate a polygon.
[src:polygon-triangulation/polygon-triangulation] It is trivial to triangulate any convex polygon in linear time into a fan triangulation, by adding diagonals from one vertex to all other non-nearest neighbor vertices.
[src:polygon-triangulation/polygon-triangulation] One way to triangulate a simple polygon is based on the two ears theorem, as the fact that any simple polygon with at least 4 vertices without holes has at least two "ears", which are triangles with two sides being the edges of the polygon and the third one completely inside it.
[src:polygon-triangulation/polygon-triangulation] The algorithm then consists of finding such an ear, removing it from the polygon (which results in a new polygon that still meets the conditions) and repeating until there is only one triangle left.
[src:polygon-triangulation/polygon-triangulation] This algorithm is easy to implement, but slower than some other algorithms, and it only works on polygons without holes.
[src:polygon-triangulation/polygon-triangulation] An implementation that keeps separate lists of convex and concave vertices will run in O(*n*2) time.
[src:polygon-triangulation/polygon-triangulation] This method is known as *ear clipping* and sometimes *ear trimming*.
[src:polygon-triangulation/polygon-triangulation] An efficient algorithm for cutting off ears was discovered by Hossam ElGindy, Hazel Everett, and Godfried Toussaint.
[src:polygon-triangulation/polygon-triangulation] A simple polygon is monotone with respect to a line L, if any line orthogonal to L intersects the polygon at most twice.
[src:polygon-triangulation/polygon-triangulation] A monotone polygon can be split into two monotone *chains*.
[src:polygon-triangulation/polygon-triangulation] A polygon that is monotone with respect to the y-axis is called *y-monotone*.
[src:polygon-triangulation/polygon-triangulation] A monotone polygon with n vertices can be triangulated in O(*n*) time.
[src:polygon-triangulation/polygon-triangulation] Assuming a given polygon is y-monotone, the greedy algorithm begins by walking on one chain of the polygon from top to bottom while adding diagonals whenever it is possible.
[src:polygon-triangulation/polygon-triangulation] It is easy to see that the algorithm can be applied to any monotone polygon.
[src:polygon-triangulation/polygon-triangulation] A monotone polygon can be triangulated in linear time with either the algorithm of A.
[src:polygon-triangulation/polygon-triangulation] Montuno, or the algorithm of Godfried Toussaint.
[src:polygon-triangulation/polygon-triangulation] If a polygon is not monotone, it can be partitioned into monotone subpolygons in O(*n* log *n*) time using a sweep-line approach.
[src:polygon-triangulation/polygon-triangulation] The algorithm does not require the polygon to be simple, thus it can be applied to polygons with holes.
[src:polygon-triangulation/polygon-triangulation] Generally, this algorithm can triangulate a planar subdivision with *n* vertices in O(*n* log *n*) time using O(*n*) space.
[src:polygon-triangulation/polygon-triangulation] A useful graph that is often associated with a triangulation of a polygon *P* is the dual graph.
[src:polygon-triangulation/polygon-triangulation] Given a triangulation *TP* of *P*, one defines the graph *G*(*TP*) as the graph whose vertex set are the triangles of *TP*, two vertices (triangles) being adjacent if and only if they share a diagonal.
[src:polygon-triangulation/polygon-triangulation] It is easy to observe that *G*(*TP*) is a tree with maximum degree 3.
[src:polygon-triangulation/polygon-triangulation] Until 1988, whether a simple polygon can be triangulated faster than O(*n* log *n*) time was an open problem in computational geometry.
[src:polygon-triangulation/polygon-triangulation] Then, Tarjan & Van Wyk (1988) discovered an O(*n* log log *n*)-time algorithm for triangulation, later simplified by Kirkpatrick, Klawe & Tarjan (1992).
[src:polygon-triangulation/polygon-triangulation] Several improved methods with complexity O(*n* log* *n*) (in practice, indistinguishable from linear time) followed.
[src:polygon-triangulation/polygon-triangulation] Bernard Chazelle showed in 1991 that any simple polygon can be triangulated in linear time, though the proposed algorithm is very complex.
[src:polygon-triangulation/polygon-triangulation] Seidel's decomposition algorithm and Chazelle's triangulation method are discussed in detail in Li & Klette (2011).
[src:polygon-triangulation/polygon-triangulation] The time complexity of triangulation of an *n*-vertex polygon *with* holes has an Ω(*n* log *n*) lower bound, in algebraic computation tree models of computation.
[src:polygon-triangulation/polygon-triangulation] It is possible to compute the number of distinct triangulations of a simple polygon in polynomial time using dynamic programming, and (based on this counting algorithm) to generate uniformly random triangulations in polynomial time.
[src:polygon-triangulation/polygon-triangulation] However, counting the triangulations of a polygon with holes is #P-complete, making it unlikely that it can be done in polynomial time.
[src:polygon-triangulation/simple-polygon] In geometry, a **simple polygon** is a polygon that does not intersect itself and has no holes.
[src:polygon-triangulation/simple-polygon] That is, it is a piecewise-linear Jordan curve consisting of finitely many line segments.
[src:polygon-triangulation/simple-polygon] These polygons include as special cases the convex polygons, star-shaped polygons, and monotone polygons.
[src:polygon-triangulation/simple-polygon] The sum of external angles of a simple polygon is $2\pi$ .
[src:polygon-triangulation/simple-polygon] Every simple polygon with n sides can be triangulated by $n-3$ of its diagonals, and by the art gallery theorem its interior is visible from some $\lfloor n/3\rfloor$ of its vertices.
[src:polygon-triangulation/simple-polygon] Simple polygons are commonly seen as the input to computational geometry problems, including point in polygon testing, area computation, the convex hull of a simple polygon, triangulation, and Euclidean shortest paths.
[src:polygon-triangulation/simple-polygon] Other constructions in geometry related to simple polygons include Schwarz–Christoffel mapping, used to find conformal maps involving simple polygons, polygonalization of point sets, constructive solid geometry formulas for polygons, and visibility graphs of polygons.
[src:polygon-triangulation/simple-polygon] A simple polygon is a closed curve in the Euclidean plane consisting of straight line segments, meeting end-to-end to form a polygonal chain.
[src:polygon-triangulation/simple-polygon] Two line segments meet at every endpoint, and there are no other points of intersection between the line segments.
[src:polygon-triangulation/simple-polygon] No proper subset of the line segments has the same properties.
[src:polygon-triangulation/simple-polygon] The qualifier *simple* is sometimes omitted, with the word *polygon* assumed to mean a simple polygon.
[src:polygon-triangulation/simple-polygon] The line segments that form a polygon are called its *edges* or *sides*.
[src:polygon-triangulation/simple-polygon] An endpoint of a segment is called a *vertex* (plural: vertices) or a *corner*.
[src:polygon-triangulation/simple-polygon] *Edges* and *vertices* are more formal, but may be ambiguous in contexts that also involve the edges and vertices of a graph; the more colloquial terms *sides* and *corners* can be used to avoid this ambiguity.
[src:polygon-triangulation/simple-polygon] The number of edges always equals the number of vertices.
[src:polygon-triangulation/simple-polygon] Some sources allow two line segments to form a straight angle (180°), while others disallow this, instead requiring collinear segments of a closed polygonal chain to be merged into a single longer side.
[src:polygon-triangulation/simple-polygon] Two vertices are *neighbors* if they are the two endpoints of one of the sides of the polygon.
[src:polygon-triangulation/simple-polygon] Simple polygons are sometimes called **Jordan polygons**, because they are Jordan curves; the Jordan curve theorem can be used to prove that such a polygon divides the plane into two regions.
[src:polygon-triangulation/simple-polygon] Indeed, Camille Jordan's original proof of this theorem took the special case of simple polygons (stated without proof) as its starting point.
[src:polygon-triangulation/simple-polygon] The region inside the polygon (its *interior*) forms a bounded set topologically equivalent to an open disk by the Jordan–Schönflies theorem, with a finite but nonzero area.
[src:polygon-triangulation/simple-polygon] The polygon itself is topologically equivalent to a circle, and the region outside (the *exterior*) is an unbounded connected open set, with infinite area.
[src:polygon-triangulation/simple-polygon] Although the formal definition of a simple polygon is typically as a system of line segments, it is also possible (and common in informal usage) to define a simple polygon as a closed set in the plane, the union of these line segments with the interior of the polygon.
[src:polygon-triangulation/simple-polygon] A *diagonal* of a simple polygon is any line segment that has two polygon vertices as its endpoints, and that otherwise is entirely interior to the polygon.
[src:polygon-triangulation/simple-polygon] The *internal angle* of a simple polygon, at one of its vertices, is the angle spanned by the interior of the polygon at that vertex.
[src:polygon-triangulation/simple-polygon] A vertex is *convex* if its internal angle is less than $\pi$ (a straight angle, 180°) and *concave* if the internal angle is greater than $\pi$ .
[src:polygon-triangulation/simple-polygon] If the internal angle is $\theta$ , the *external angle* at the same vertex is defined to be its supplement $\pi -\theta$ , the turning angle from one directed side to the next.
[src:polygon-triangulation/simple-polygon] The external angle is positive at a convex vertex or negative at a concave vertex.
[src:polygon-triangulation/simple-polygon] For every simple polygon, the sum of the external angles is $2\pi$ (one full turn, 360°).
[src:polygon-triangulation/simple-polygon] Thus the sum of the internal angles, for a simple polygon with n sides is $(n-2)\pi$ .
[src:polygon-triangulation/simple-polygon] Every simple polygon can be partitioned into non-overlapping triangles by a subset of its diagonals.
[src:polygon-triangulation/simple-polygon] When the polygon has n sides, this produces $n-2$ triangles, separated by $n-3$ diagonals.
[src:polygon-triangulation/simple-polygon] The resulting partition is called a *polygon triangulation*.
[src:polygon-triangulation/simple-polygon] The shape of a triangulated simple polygon can be uniquely determined by the internal angles of the polygon and by the cross-ratios of the quadrilaterals formed by pairs of triangles that share a diagonal.
[src:polygon-triangulation/simple-polygon] According to the two ears theorem, every simple polygon that is not a triangle has at least two *ears*, vertices whose two neighbors are the endpoints of a diagonal.
[src:polygon-triangulation/simple-polygon] A related theorem states that every simple polygon that is not a convex polygon has a *mouth*, a vertex whose two neighbors are the endpoints of a line segment that is otherwise entirely exterior to the polygon.
[src:polygon-triangulation/simple-polygon] The polygons that have exactly two ears and one mouth are called *anthropomorphic polygons*.
[src:polygon-triangulation/simple-polygon] According to the art gallery theorem, in a simple polygon with n vertices, it is always possible to find a subset of at most $\lfloor n/3\rfloor$ of the vertices with the property that every point in the polygon is visible from one of the selected vertices.
[src:polygon-triangulation/simple-polygon] This means that, for each point p in the polygon, there exists a line segment connecting p to a selected vertex, passing only through interior points of the polygon.
[src:polygon-triangulation/simple-polygon] One way to prove this is to use graph coloring on a triangulation of the polygon: it is always possible to color the vertices with three colors, so that each side or diagonal in the triangulation has two endpoints of different colors.
[src:polygon-triangulation/simple-polygon] Each point of the polygon is visible to a vertex of each color, for instance one of the three vertices of the triangle containing that point in the chosen triangulation.
[src:polygon-triangulation/simple-polygon] One of the colors is used by at most $\lfloor n/3\rfloor$ of the vertices, proving the theorem.
[src:polygon-triangulation/simple-polygon] Every convex polygon is a simple polygon.
[src:polygon-triangulation/simple-polygon] Another important class of simple polygons are the star-shaped polygons, the polygons that have a point (interior or on their boundary) from which every point is visible.
[src:polygon-triangulation/simple-polygon] A monotone polygon, with respect to a straight line L , is a polygon for which every line perpendicular to L intersects the interior of the polygon in a connected set.
[src:polygon-triangulation/simple-polygon] Equivalently, it is a polygon whose boundary can be partitioned into two monotone polygonal chains, subsequences of edges whose vertices, when projected perpendicularly onto L , have the same order along L as they do in the chain.
[src:polygon-triangulation/simple-polygon] In computational geometry, several important computational tasks involve inputs in the form of a simple polygon.
[src:polygon-triangulation/simple-polygon] Researchers have also studied producing other polygons from simple polygons using their offset curves, unions and intersections, and Minkowski sums, but these operations do not always produce a simple polygon as their result.
[src:polygon-triangulation/simple-polygon] They can be defined in a way that always produces a two-dimensional region, but this requires careful definitions of the intersection and difference operations in order to avoid creating one-dimensional features or isolated points.
[src:polygon-triangulation/simple-polygon] According to the Riemann mapping theorem, any simply connected open subset of the plane can be conformally mapped onto a disk.
[src:polygon-triangulation/simple-polygon] Schwarz–Christoffel mapping provides a method to explicitly construct a map from a disk to any simple polygon using specified vertex angles and pre-images of the polygon vertices on the boundary of the disk.
[src:polygon-triangulation/simple-polygon] These *pre-vertices* are typically computed numerically.
[src:polygon-triangulation/simple-polygon] Every finite set of points in the plane that does not lie on a single line can be connected to form the vertices of a simple polygon (allowing 180° angles); for instance, one such polygon is the solution to the traveling salesperson problem.
[src:polygon-triangulation/simple-polygon] Connecting points to form a polygon in this way is called polygonalization.
[src:polygon-triangulation/simple-polygon] Every simple polygon can be represented by a formula in constructive solid geometry that constructs the polygon (as a closed set including the interior) from unions and intersections of half-planes, with each side of the polygon appearing once as a half-plane in the formula.
[src:polygon-triangulation/simple-polygon] Converting an n -sided polygon into this representation can be performed in time $O(n\log n)$ .
[src:polygon-triangulation/simple-polygon] The visibility graph of a simple polygon connects its vertices by edges representing the sides and diagonals of the polygon.
[src:polygon-triangulation/simple-polygon] It always contains a Hamiltonian cycle, formed by the polygon sides.
[src:polygon-triangulation/simple-polygon] The computational complexity of reconstructing a polygon that has a given graph as its visibility graph, with a specified Hamiltonian cycle as its cycle of sides, remains an open problem.
[src:polygon-triangulation/two-ears-theorem] In geometry, the **two ears theorem** states that every simple polygon with more than three vertices has at least two ears, vertices that can be removed from the polygon without introducing any crossings.
[src:polygon-triangulation/two-ears-theorem] The two ears theorem is equivalent to the existence of polygon triangulations.
[src:polygon-triangulation/two-ears-theorem] Meisters, but was proved earlier by Max Dehn.
[src:polygon-triangulation/two-ears-theorem] A simple polygon is a simple closed curve in the Euclidean plane consisting of finitely many line segments in a cyclic sequence, with each two consecutive line segments meeting at a common endpoint, and no other intersections.
[src:polygon-triangulation/two-ears-theorem] By the Jordan curve theorem, it separates the plane into two regions, one of which (the interior of the polygon) is bounded.
[src:polygon-triangulation/two-ears-theorem] An *ear* of a polygon is defined as a triangle formed by three consecutive vertices $u,v,w$ of the polygon, such that its edge $uw$ lies entirely in the interior of the polygon.
[src:polygon-triangulation/two-ears-theorem] The two ears theorem states that every simple polygon that is not itself a triangle has at least two ears.
[src:polygon-triangulation/two-ears-theorem] An ear and its two neighbors form a triangle within the polygon that is not crossed by any other part of the polygon.
[src:polygon-triangulation/two-ears-theorem] Removing a triangle of this type produces a polygon with fewer sides, and repeatedly removing ears allows any simple polygon to be triangulated.
[src:polygon-triangulation/two-ears-theorem] Conversely, if a polygon is triangulated, the weak dual of the triangulation (a graph with one vertex per triangle and one edge per pair of adjacent triangles) will be a tree and each leaf of the tree will form an ear.
[src:polygon-triangulation/two-ears-theorem] Since every tree with more than one vertex has at least two leaves, every triangulated polygon with more than one triangle has at least two ears.
[src:polygon-triangulation/two-ears-theorem] Thus, the two ears theorem is equivalent to the fact that every simple polygon has a triangulation.
[src:polygon-triangulation/two-ears-theorem] Triangulation algorithms based on this principle have been called *ear-clipping algorithms*.
[src:polygon-triangulation/two-ears-theorem] Although a naive implementation is slow, ear-clipping can be sped up by the observation that a triple of consecutive vertices of a polygon forms an ear if and only if the central vertex of the triple is convex and the triple forms a triangle that does not contain any reflex vertices.
[src:polygon-triangulation/two-ears-theorem] By maintaining a queue of triples with this property, and repeatedly removing an ear from the queue and updating the adjacent triples, it is possible to perform ear-clipping in time $O{\bigl (}n(r+1){\bigr )}$ , where n is the number of input vertices and r is the number of reflex vertices.
[src:polygon-triangulation/two-ears-theorem] If a simple polygon is triangulated, then a triple of consecutive vertices $u,v,w$ forms an ear if v is a convex vertex and none of its other neighbors in the triangulation lie in triangle $uvw$ .
[src:polygon-triangulation/two-ears-theorem] By testing all neighbors of all vertices, it is possible to find all the ears of a triangulated simple polygon in linear time.
[src:polygon-triangulation/two-ears-theorem] Alternatively, it is also possible to find a single ear of a simple polygon in linear time, without triangulating the polygon.
[src:polygon-triangulation/two-ears-theorem] An ear is called *exposed* when its central vertex belongs to the convex hull of the polygon.
[src:polygon-triangulation/two-ears-theorem] However, it is possible for a polygon to have no exposed ears.
[src:polygon-triangulation/two-ears-theorem] Ears are a special case of a *principal vertex*, a vertex such that the line segment connecting the vertex's neighbors does not cross the polygon or touch any other vertex of it.
[src:polygon-triangulation/two-ears-theorem] A principal vertex for which this line segment lies outside the polygon is called a *mouth*.
[src:polygon-triangulation/two-ears-theorem] Analogously to the two ears theorem, every non-convex simple polygon has at least one mouth.
[src:polygon-triangulation/two-ears-theorem] Polygons with the minimum number of principal vertices of both types, two ears and a mouth, are called anthropomorphic polygons.
[src:polygon-triangulation/two-ears-theorem] Repeatedly finding and removing a mouth from a non-convex polygon will eventually turn it into the convex hull of the initial polygon.
[src:polygon-triangulation/two-ears-theorem] This principle can be applied to the *surrounding polygons* of a set of points; these are polygons that use some of the points as vertices, and contain the rest of them.
[src:polygon-triangulation/two-ears-theorem] Removing a mouth from a surrounding polygon produces another surrounding polygon, and the family of all surrounding polygons can be found by reversing this mouth-removal process, starting from the convex hull.
[src:polygon-triangulation/two-ears-theorem] Let v be a vertex that is preceded by vertex u and proceeded by vertex w .
[src:polygon-triangulation/two-ears-theorem] We say that v is a **convex corner** if there is a point A on the edge $uv$ and a point B on the edge $vw$ such that the line $AB$ lies within the polygon.
[src:polygon-triangulation/two-ears-theorem] If the points $A,B$ were the vertices $u,v$ then we would have an ear - but in general there are corners that are not ears.
[src:polygon-triangulation/two-ears-theorem] Every simple polygon has at least three **convex corners**.
[src:polygon-triangulation/two-ears-theorem] If one of these vertices, v, is not an ear, then it can be connected by a diagonal to another vertex x inside the triangle uvw formed by v and its two neighbors; x can be chosen to be the vertex within this triangle that is farthest from line uw.
[src:polygon-triangulation/two-ears-theorem] This diagonal decomposes the polygon into two smaller polygons, and repeated decomposition by ears and diagonals eventually produces a triangulation of the whole polygon, from which an ear can be found as a leaf of the dual tree.
[src:polygon-triangulation/two-ears-theorem] The two ears theorem is often attributed to a 1975 paper by Gary H.
[src:polygon-triangulation/two-ears-theorem] Meisters, from which the "ear" terminology originated.
[src:polygon-triangulation/two-ears-theorem] However, the theorem was proved earlier by Max Dehn (circa 1899) as part of a proof of the Jordan curve theorem.
[src:polygon-triangulation/two-ears-theorem] The proof presented in this article follows Dehn's.
